						<summary>

						<p>On a broken pillar lying in the main street. </p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">1109 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This fragmentary record seems to have contained a genealogical account of the Chālukya family. It refers to <hi rend="italic">mahādānās</hi> such as <hi rend="italic">guḍaparvata, śarkaraparvata, lavaṇaparvata</hi> and <hi rend="italic">gōsahasra.</hi> Also, it refers to an officer Kānadēva who bears the epithets <hi rend="italic">antahpura verggaḍe, mahāpradhāna, kannada-sandhivigrahi</hi> and <hi rend="italic">daṇḍanāyaka.</hi> In the post script Appēśvara-dēva is mentioned.</p>						

						<p>It is dated in the Chalukya Vikrama year 3(1), Virōdhi, Akshaya (tritīya) which is irregular. If the given Chalukya Vikrama varsha 3(1) is a mistake for 34 then the cyclic year Virōdhi holds good [with Śaka 1031] and the given tithi corresponds with 1109 A.D., April 5, Monday.</p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
